title: For Sale:  Scam Warning on Scar 17S and Other Firearms!
location: Throughout US, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
Profit from my misfortune! I was recently taken in by a scammer who is using Scar 17S and other firearms as bait. The scammer(s) is using past listings on gun forums, copying them, and posting them here. An easy way to check for this is to right click the image, select "Search Google for this Image" (if using Google Chrome) and seeing what pops up. Just today I flagged a listing for a 17S, FDE, advertised as an Ohio gun. The image search found the original 2011 listing here: http://fnforum.net/forums/fn-guns-fn-items-sale/24175-wts-fde-scar-17s-lnib-unfired.html

The scammer is pretty sophisticated. If he follows the same approach, he'll first ask you to go through PayPal. He will claim that he can't get the money from PayPal into his bank, and then refund your money. He'll then ask for a wire. Once wired, his wife will die, he'll wind up in the hospital, and well, say goodbye to your $.

title: For Sale:  SUPER EARLY RIFLE...THE 5th S-C EVER MADE...C&R
location: Meadville / Grove City, Meadville / Grove City, Pennsylvania
postcontent: Here is the 5th Smith-Corona U.S. Model 03-A3 ever made! The Model 03-A3 was produced by both Remington and Smith-Corona during WWII. A somewhat simplified version of the famous Springfield Model 1903, the 03-A3 incorporated some stamped parts, a re-positioned rear sight that was more combat-effective, and a few other modifications designed to speed production. Due to the pressing need for arms and with Remington struggling to increase production, it was decided a second prime contractor for the 03-A3 was needed. Smith-Corona was selected and tooled up for production. S-C was eventually awarded a contract for 300,000 rifles and was assigned the serial number blocks 3,608,000-3,707,999 and 4,708,000-4,992,000. The first "pilot" batch of 20 rifles was produced in October, 1942. This rifle, serial number 3,608,004 is the FIFTH RIFLE in the first block and is likely one of the "pilot" rifles manufactured in October, 1942. These earliest rifles have some unusual features including a SIX-groove barrel that was manufactured by Savage (rather than the High Standard 4-groove commonly seen). This rifle has the 6-groove barrel which is marked on top, behind the front sight, with a small "ordnance bomb" and a punch mark. The underside is marked with a "P" proof. The barrel profile is somewhat unusual also with the first 7/16" of the muzzle turned down to 0.618" before stepping up to a normal profile. Additionally, the left receiver rail has no "thumb relief" cut for stripper clip loading normally found in "regular production". Overall condition is quite good and the rifle retains almost all of the original finish on the receiver and barrel. The "X" marked Smith-Corona bolt is blued, has an Smith-Corona "S" marked extractor, scalloped Smith-Corona bolt sleeve, and an "R" marked Remington cocking piece. The stamped trigger guard/floor plate is of Remington manufacture and parkerized. The stock has a faintly visible FJA cartouche, a 7/16" circled-P proof behind the trigger guard, and no rebuild markings. The stock is free of cracks or chips although it does exhibit some normal handling wear. The buttplate is of S-C manufacture, as are the barrel bands. The rifle appears to be in excellent mechanical condition. The bore is likewise excellent with bright, sharp rifling and low throat and muzzle erosion readings. This is an interesting rifle and a unique

title: For Sale/Trade:  My .22LR Savage for your...
postcontent:
I've got an older Savage MK-II (pre- accu-trigger) up for sale/trade.  Metal was re-blued awhile back, and barrel/receiver/bold are in excellent shape, with no pitting or rust.  Synthetic stock has a couple of nicks/dings, but nothing bad, and so minor I can't get them to show up in photos.  Bore is in excellent shape, and the entire firearm is well-cleaned and stored with a healthy coating of oil.
  I received this gun in trade a while back, and have only had it to the range once.  I manage to shoot several consecutive .5"-1" groups at 25 yards, using the stock notch-and-ball iron sights and run-of-the-mill Federal 36-gr HP ammo, shooting from the prone.  I suspect that with a little polish to the trigger and about $50.00 to mount a scope, you'll be getting close to 1 MOA with this little guy!

Firearm will include two 10-round magazines, and UP TO a 525-rd brick of .22LR ammo (ammo will depend on your offer).  I would sell the rifle with the mags and brick of ammo or $175.00 (FIRM!), but prefer to trade for items listed below.

Will need to see GA State ID or Military ID with Active Duty orders, and must be willing to sign a bill of sale (solely for my records).  Thanks or looking!
